---
description: Enforce architecture discipline (decoupling, DI, pattern-fit) and block broad refactors without explicit approval.
alwaysApply: true
---

# architecture-governance

MODE: ALWAYS_ON
INTENT: preserve design integrity; prevent convenience-driven coupling and opportunistic rewrites

PRINCIPLES:
- SRP: one clear reason to change per unit
- OCP: extend via new collaborators/interfaces before modifying stable core flows
- DIP: high-level policy depends on abstractions, not concrete infrastructure
- DECOUPLING: enforce boundary direction UI -> application/domain -> data/infrastructure; no inward leaks

DEPENDENCY_INJECTION:
- DEFAULT: constructor injection preferred for required dependencies
- FACTORIES: use factory/provider composition at boundaries; avoid hidden service lookups in core logic
- FORBIDDEN: direct singleton/global access inside domain/application logic unless project rule explicitly allows
- TESTABILITY: dependency seams must allow unit tests without platform/network/database side effects

DESIGN_PATTERNS:
- APPLY_WHEN_NEEDED: choose simplest pattern that solves current requirement; no speculative pattern layering
- REQUIRED_FOR_DECISIONS: before introducing/changing pattern, state context, forces, why this pattern, why alternatives rejected
- CONSISTENCY: prefer existing project pattern vocabulary and naming over novel variants
- EXIT_CRITERIA: if pattern adds indirection without measurable clarity/testability/reuse gain, remove or do not introduce

REFACTOR_GUARDRAILS:
- DEFAULT_SCOPE: change only request-scoped modules
- NO_DRIVE_BY_REFACTOR: do not refactor adjacent areas unless required for correctness or requested
- BROAD_REFACTOR_GATE: if change crosses bounded contexts/layers or renames many files, pause and ask explicit confirmation
- LEGACY_CODE_TOUCH: when legacy design is imperfect but unrelated, document risk and defer instead of widening scope

ARCH_REVIEW_BEFORE_EDIT:
- step 1 -> map affected layer boundaries and dependency directions
- step 2 -> list interfaces/contracts to preserve
- step 3 -> define minimal change set and why alternatives are out of scope
- verify: plan keeps dependency direction and reduces or preserves coupling

DONE_CRITERIA:
- ARCH_PARITY: no new boundary violation; no new hidden dependency source
- DI_PARITY: new dependencies injected explicitly and mockable in tests
- PATTERN_JUSTIFIED: non-trivial pattern additions include short rationale in PR/notes
- VERIFY: run relevant tests/lints for touched modules before claiming completion

ESCALATE:
- if requested change conflicts with boundary direction or DIP, stop and request architectural decision
- if user explicitly requests broad refactor, proceed only with stated scope + risk confirmation
